  "voiceNotes": "Jordan never lets a silence sit — 'okay but anyway' is his reset button, and he touches shoulders/arms to keep the social temperature warm even when he's anxious underneath. He laughs a half-second before jokes land because he needs the room to feel good more than he needs the joke to actually be funny. Priya punches down softly and always leaves herself a technical out ('It's a joke. Everyone laughed... didn't they?') — her cruelty is procedural, not personal, which is what makes it worse. She never apologizes in words; the closest she gets is a dropped subject or a real nod, never a sentence. Alex answers in the fewest words that will get them out of a conversation alive, and every joke arrives about one beat late, like they had to check it was safe first. Their deflections ('It's fine,' 'I'm good, really') are doors closing gently, not slamming — that's what makes them land harder. Sol's internal voice is the most self-aware character in the room but her spoken voice lags behind it — she performs ease a half-second late, same as her laugh, and the gap between what she says and what she thinks (INTERNAL lines) is the whole emotional engine of the episode. When she's about to risk something real, let the sentence get shorter, not longer.",
